fynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales"},"cs":{"ABT    1202–":"okolo 1202–Zesnulý","1202–Male":"1202–Zesnulý","–Male":"Zesnulý","1195–Female":"1195–Zesnulá","1230–Male":"1230–Zesnulý","1181–Male":"1181–Zesnulý","ABT    1202":"okolo 1202","1202":"1202","ABT    1230":"okolo 1230","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1181":"1181","of,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","of Y Fforest,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales"},"da":{"ABT    1202–":"omkring 1202–Afdød","1202–Male":"1202–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1195–Female":"1195–Afdød","1230–Male":"1230–Afdød","1181–Male":"1181–Afdød","ABT    1202":"omkring 1202","1202":"1202","ABT    1230":"omkring 1230","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1181":"1181","of,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","of Y Fforest,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales"},"nl":{"ABT    1202–":"circa 1202–Overleden","1202–Male":"1202–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1195–Female":"1195–Overleden","1230–Male":"1230–Overleden","1181–Male":"1181–Overleden","ABT    1202":"circa 1202","1202":"1202","ABT    1230":"circa 1230","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1181":"1181","of,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","of Y Fforest,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales"},"en":{"ABT    1202–":"about 1202–Deceased","1202–Male":"1202–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1195–Female":"1195–Deceased","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","1181–Male":"1181–Deceased","ABT    1202":"about 1202","1202":"1202","ABT    1230":"about 1230","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1181":"1181","of,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","of Y Fforest,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Holland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish, French, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from <i>Holland</i>, a province of the Netherlands.","English: habitational name from Downholland or Upholland (Lancashire), Hulland (Derbyshire), the Parts of Holland, one of the three administrative subdivisions of Lincolnshire, any of the four places called Hoyland (southern Yorkshire), and possibly Great and Little Holland (Essex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","English: habitational name either from Hoeland (Farm) in Bury (Sussex), or from Holland's Barn in Albourne (Sussex). The placename in Bury has the same etymology as in 1 above, while the placename in Albourne may derive from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hollands","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  , especially 3, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Dutch: genitivized form of   Holland  ."]},{"name":"Howland","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Hovland  .","History: Howland was the name of three Quaker brothers, original settlers in Marshfield, MA. They were from Huntingdonshire, England. The eldest, John Howland (<i>c.</i> 1593–1672) was a passenger on the <i>Mayflower</i>, servant to Gov. John Carver, who died in the first winter at Plymouth Colony."]},{"name":"Hollander","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Den Hollander</b>), German (also <b>Holländer</b>), English, Swedish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Holland (see   Holland   1)."]},{"name":"Holand","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Holland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from about twenty farmsteads so named, composed of Old Norse <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, field’, denoting a high-lying farm."]},{"name":"Aland","meanings":["Scandinavian (<b>Åland</b>): topographic name from the Åland Islands in the Gulf of Bothnia.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>atte lande</i> (Old French <i>laund</i>) ‘dweller at the glade or pasture’, or sometimes perhaps, ‘dweller at the old cultivated land(s)’ from Old English <i>eald</i>, <i>ald</i> ‘old’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]},{"name":"Hollon","meanings":["English: altered form of   Holland  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert ap Holland was born about 1202, in Breconshire, Wales as the son of gg- son Holland. He had at least 1 son with Miss ferch Ifor."},"et":{"ABT    1202–":"umbes 1202–Surnud","1202–Male":"1202–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1181–Male":"1181–Surnud","ABT    1202":"umbes 1202","1202":"1202","ABT    1230":"umbes 1230","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1181":"1181","of,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","of Y Fforest,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales"},"fi":{"ABT    1202–":"noin 1202–Kuollut","1202–Male":"1202–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1195–Female":"1195–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1181–Male":"1181–Kuollut","ABT    1202":"noin 1202","1202":"1202","ABT    1230":"noin 1230","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1181":"1181","of,Defynnog,Breconshire